    "id": "fertile_window",
    "title": "Understanding Your Fertile Window",
    "category": "Fertility",
    "readTime": "7 min read",
    "summary": "Discover what the fertile window is, how long it lasts, and how to identify your most fertile days.",
    "content": "# Understanding Your Fertile Window\n\nThe fertile window refers to the days during a menstrual cycle when pregnancy is most likely to occur.\n\nUnderstanding your fertile window can help you make informed decisions about family planning and reproductive health.\n\n## What Is The Fertile Window?\n\nPregnancy can occur when sperm meet an egg.\n\nBecause sperm can survive inside the reproductive tract for several days, the fertile window includes the days leading up to ovulation and the day of ovulation itself.\n\nFor many people, the fertile window lasts approximately six days.\n\n## Why Six Days?\n\nSperm may survive for up to five days under ideal conditions.\n\nThe egg survives for about 12 to 24 hours after ovulation.\n\nThis creates a limited period during which fertilization can occur.\n\n## Signs You May Be In Your Fertile Window\n\nCommon signs include:\n\n• Clear, stretchy cervical mucus\n• Increased libido\n• Higher energy levels\n• Increased vaginal lubrication\n• Mild ovulation pain\n• Feeling more social or confident\n\n## Tracking Your Fertile Window\n\nMethods include:\n\n### Cycle Tracking\n\nRecording menstrual cycles helps estimate ovulation timing.\n\n### Cervical Mucus Monitoring\n\nEgg-white cervical mucus is often associated with peak fertility.\n\n### Basal Body Temperature\n\nA slight temperature rise typically occurs after ovulation.\n\n### Ovulation Predictor Kits\n\nThese detect LH surges that occur before ovulation.\n\n## Fertility Is Not Guaranteed\n\nEven during the fertile window, pregnancy is not guaranteed.\n\nMany factors influence fertility including age, health conditions, sperm quality, and overall reproductive health.\n\n## Common Myth\n\nMyth: You can only get pregnant on the day you ovulate.\n\nFact: Pregnancy can occur from intercourse in the days before ovulation because sperm can survive for several days.\n\n## Quick Summary\n\nThe fertile window typically includes the five days before ovulation and the day of ovulation. Tracking cervical mucus, cycle length, and ovulation signs can help identify your most fertile days."
