    "content": "# First Trimester Pregnancy Guide\n\nThe first trimester covers weeks 1 through 12 of pregnancy.\n\nThis is a period of rapid growth and development for the baby and significant changes for the mother.\n\n## Baby's Development\n\nDuring the first trimester:\n\n• The brain begins developing\n• The heart starts beating\n• Major organs begin forming\n• Arms and legs develop\n• Facial features start appearing\n\nBy the end of the first trimester, most major organ systems have begun developing.\n\n## Common Symptoms\n\nMany people experience:\n\n• Fatigue\n• Nausea\n• Vomiting\n• Breast tenderness\n• Food aversions\n• Frequent urination\n• Mood changes\n• Bloating\n\n## Healthy Habits During The First Trimester\n\n### Prioritize Nutrition\n\nFocus on:\n\n• Fruits\n• Vegetables\n• Whole grains\n• Lean proteins\n• Healthy fats\n\n### Stay Hydrated\n\nAdequate hydration supports both maternal and fetal health.\n\n### Rest When Needed\n\nFatigue is extremely common during early pregnancy.\n\n### Attend Prenatal Appointments\n\nRegular prenatal care helps monitor pregnancy health and development.\n\n## Warning Signs\n\nSeek medical advice if you experience:\n\n• Severe abdominal pain\n• Heavy bleeding\n• Severe dehydration\n• Persistent vomiting\n• High fever\n\n## Emotional Changes\n\nHormonal fluctuations can affect emotions.\n\nExperiencing a range of feelings is normal during this transition.\n\n## Common Myth\n\nMyth: Exercise should be completely avoided during pregnancy.\n\nFact: Many people can safely continue appropriate physical activity after consulting a healthcare professional.\n\n## Quick Summary\n\nThe first trimester is a period of rapid development and major physical changes. Healthy nutrition, hydration, rest, and prenatal care help support a healthy pregnancy."
